In [[toxicology]], the '''margin of exposure''' (or '''MOE''') of a substance is the ratio of its [[no-observed-adverse-effect level]] to its theoretical, predicted, or estimated dose or concentration of human intake.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Benford|first1=Diane|last2=Bolger|first2=P. Michael|last3=Carthew|first3=Philip|last4=Coulet|first4=Myriam|last5=DiNovi|first5=Michael|last6=Leblanc|first6=Jean-Charles|last7=Renwick|first7=Andrew G.|last8=Setzer|first8=Woodrow|last9=Schlatter|first9=Josef|last10=Smith|first10=Benjamin|last11=Slob|first11=Wout|last12=Williams|first12=Gary|last13=Wildemann|first13=Tanja|title=Application of the Margin of Exposure (MOE) approach to substances in food that are genotoxic and carcinogenic|journal=Food and Chemical Toxicology|date=January 2010|volume=48|pages=S2–S24|doi=10.1016/j.fct.2009.11.003}}</ref> It is used in [[risk assessment]] to determine the dangerousness of substances that are both [[genotoxic]] and [[carcinogenic]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.efsa.europa.eu/en/topics/topic/margin-exposure | title=Margin of Exposure approach developed by EFSA | work=EFSA | accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> This approach is preferred by both the [[World Health Organization]] and the [[European Food Safety Authority]] for the evaluation of the risk of carcinogens.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lachenmeier|first1=Dirk W.|last2=Przybylski|first2=Maria C.|last3=Rehm|first3=Jürgen|title=Comparative risk assessment of carcinogens in alcoholic beverages using the margin of exposure approach|journal=International Journal of Cancer|date=15 September 2012|volume=131|issue=6|pages=E995–E1003|doi=10.1002/ijc.27553|pmid=22447328}}</ref>

